article.headline: Michigan 62, Army 50
article.story: ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- Reed Baker scored 19 points in his first start as Michigan's reserves led the way in a 62-50 victory over Army on Thursday night. DeShawn Sims, also in his first start, added 13 points for the Wolverines (12-2). Ekpe Udoh scored eight points and blocked nine shots. Jarell Brown had 22 points for the Black Knights, who got seven assists from Marcus Nelson. Five days removed from an embarrassing 92-55 loss at No. 1 UCLA, Michigan coach Tommy Amaker benched his starters, and the reserves more than held their own as Michigan took a 38-25 lead into intermission. Army (9-4) led 17-15 with eight minutes to play in the opening half but Michigan ended the half with a 23-8 run. The Wolverines' Jerret Smith has the first half's final goal, a running 3-pointer released as the buzzer sounded. Army was cold from the field in the second half and rarely trailed by less than 10 points. Michigan outrebounded the Black Knights 42-27.
